canonical:
  title: 故相安竹屋像贊
  author: 崔瀣
  language: lzh
  text: 衣冠整肅狀貌端嚴律身寧儉而毋華臨事有勤而不迫進處論思之地足以福三韓退休空寂之鄕亦自高一世黃豫章離塵有髮謝康樂成佛在家人言風度肖先公我道典刑觀後嗣
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 故相安竹屋像贊
  author: 崔瀣
  language: lzh
  text: 衣冠整肅。狀貌端嚴。律身寧儉而毋華。臨事有勤而不迫。進處論思之地。足以福三韓。退休空寂之鄕。亦自高一世。黃豫章離塵有髮。謝康樂成佛在家。人言風度肖先公。我道典刑觀後嗣。
korean:
  title: 고상 안죽옥 상찬
  author: 최해
  language: kor
  text: 의관이 정숙하며 외모가 단아하다. 몸을 단속함에는 차라리 검소할지언정 화려하지 않았으며, 일에 대하여는 부지런히 하면서도 서두르지 않았다. 국사를 의논하는 자리에 나와서는 삼한(三韓)을 복되게 할 수 있으며, 적적한 시골에 물러가 있어도 또한 한 세상을 초월하였다. 황예장(黃豫章)은 속세를 떠나 있으면서도 머리를 깎지 않았고 사강락(謝康樂)은 부처가 되고서도 가정에 있었다. 사람들은 공의 풍채가 아버지를 닮았다고들 하는데, 나는 그의 모습을 적어서 후손에게 보이려 하노라.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0540_010_0150&viewSync=OT
  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 고상 안죽옥 상찬(故相安竹屋像贊) : '
    value: 그의 아들 익지(益之)를 위하여 지었다.
english:
  title: In Praise of the Late Prime Minister's Portrait in the Bamboo Cottage
  author: Choe Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    His robes and cap sit with dignity,
    His face composed and grave.
    In governing himself, he chose simplicity over splendor,
    In all matters, diligent yet never rushed.

    When called to counsel on affairs of state,
    He could bring blessing to the Three Hans,
    Yet retreating to the quiet countryside,
    He rose above the concerns of his generation.

    Huang Yuzhang dwelt apart from dust while keeping his hair uncut,
    Xie Kangshan became a Buddha while remaining in his home.
    Others speak of how his bearing resembled his father's,
    But I inscribe his likeness to show posterity his true form.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Three Hans' refers to the traditional three kingdoms of Korea (Goguryeo, Baekje, and Silla), here representing the entire realm.
  - key: ''
    value: Huang Yuzhang and Xie Kangshan are classical Chinese exemplars of the sage who withdraws from the world while maintaining spiritual purity, and the sage who remains in society yet transcends worldly concerns, respectively.
  - key: ''
    value: This portrait inscription was written for the subject's son, Yi-ji (益之).
